ICT 782 - Day 5 Notes¶

Plotting and Visualization¶

An important part of data analysis is visualization. This includes producing appealing visualizations of both cleaned and transformed data as well as the results of our analyses. Today, we will explore various plot types available in Matplotlib and, by extension, for pandas objects.

Before we proceed with plotting, we recall some basic rules for visually presenting data:

  1. Make the scale of your graphic clear. For non-negative numerical data, the vertical axis should start at 0. For numerical data on the horizontal axis, use the full range of available data.
  2. Say something. Don't produce a plot where no plot is necessary. Conversely, a single plot will eliminate the need for complicated explanations.
  3. Use the right plot for the right data. Don't use a bar chart when you really want a histogram. Similarly, don't use a pie chart when a bar chart will more clearer make the point.
  4. Use colors and style to make your point clearer, not less clear. Don't label every single data point, and don't use Excel-style 3D plots - they are nearly impossible to read. 3D plots are ok in some cases, just be judicious.

For a complete guide to plotting, check out the book 'Graphic Presentation' by Willard C. Brinton. This book was published in 1939, but most of the plot styles are still in current use, and the principles of good visualization are timeless!

Matplotlib¶

Though there are many sophisticated plotting packages for Python, Matplotlib is the foundational plotting package. Based on NumPy, Matplotlib works beautifully with pandas objects. There are many modules contained in Matplotlib. For general plotting, we'll import the Pyplot module under the alias plt.

The cell magic %matplotlib inline tells the Jupyter notebook to allow plotting after the cell in which it is called. This cell magic only needs to be called once per notebook.

In [17]:
%matplotlib inline

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

Before we dig into the details of the package, let's see an example.

Loading and displaying images with Matplotlib¶

As mentioned briefly on Day 1, Matplotlib has Matlab-like tools for loading and displaying images. Using the image module of Matplotlib, we can call the imread(<filepath>) function to load an image into the interpreter. We then use the imshow() function from the pyplot module to display the image. I often place a semi-colon after the imshow() function is called to suppress printing the object type to the console.

Since the cameraman.jpg image is grayscale, we'll specify the colormap using the keyworded argument cmap = 'gray'.

In [28]:
import matplotlib.image as mp

im = mp.imread('cameraman.jpg')
plt.imshow(im, cmap = 'gray');

Some common colormaps (the cmap argument) are bone, gray, hot, and summer.

Side note: Another way to display images in Jupyter notebooks is with the ![hover text](image filepath) syntax.

Matplotlib objects: the structure of plots¶

There are, of course, shortcuts to plotting with Matplotlib. However, understanding the underlying structure of Matplotlib plots opens a much wider range of customizable plots. In this section, we'll explore the fundamental objects in Matplotlib.

The figure object¶

The most basic object in Matplotlib is the figure. This object contains attributes for the plotting metadata such as the axes, the plot resolution, the size of the plot, and the background color. When we generate a figure, we can also specify its number attribute so that we can access various figure objects by their number. All plotting metadata attributes can be passed as keyworded arguments, and are summarized in the following table.

Optional Attribute Options Details Default
num Integer or string Sets the number attribute for the figure object None
figsize (float, float) Sets the size of the figure object to (width, height) in inches. (6.4, 4.8)
dpi Integer Sets the figure resolution in dots per inch. 100
facecolor Specified color or RGB tuple. w, white
r, red
g, green
b, blue
c, cyan
y, yellow
m, magenta
k, black		 Sets the background color of the figure. w or white
edgecolor Specified color or RGB tuple. (see facecolor) Sets the border color of the figure. w or white
frameon bool True, False If False, don't draw the frame of the figure object. True
In [29]:
fig1 = plt.figure(num = 1, 
                  figsize = (10, 5), 
                  dpi = 250, 
                  facecolor = 'm', 
                  edgecolor = 'k')

<Figure size 2500x1250 with 0 Axes>

Note that we passed in inches for the figsize attribute, but the figure has its size determined by pixels. This is because the dpi value is literally dots per inch. In other words, we specify the pixels per square inch and the figsize, and the Python interpreter does the arithmetic for us.

When fig1 was generated, the console output was <Figure size 2500x1250 with 0 Axes>. This tells us that we have an empty figure object. We'll now focus on the second important object in Matplotlib: the axes object.

The axes object¶

With a figure generated, we can place an axes object onto it. Think of this as creating a canvas (generating the figure) and then preparing an area of the canvas for your painting (generating the axes). We will use the add_subplot() method of the figure object to add an axes to our figure.

In [30]:
ax1 = fig1.add_subplot()

We didn't specify any arguments for the add_subplot() method. However, the default argument is 1,1,1 or, equivalently, 111. These positional arguments are not specified in the official documentation as keyworded arguments, which makes them unnecessarily vague. However, they mean number_of_rows, number_of_columns, index. In other words, they specify the number of sub-plots our figure will have and the position of our generated axes object.

By passing in 1,1,1, we are telling the figure that we want a sub-plot with 1 row, 1 column, and the axes object is in index position 1. Index positions are read left-to-right, top-to-bottom.

Example: Plotting with figure and axes objects¶

This might be confusing, so let's actually plot some axes to see what's going on. We'll create a new figure and two axes objects. To identify our axes positions, we'll use the set_title() method.

In [51]:
fig = plt.figure(num = 2, 
                 figsize = (10, 4), 
                 dpi = 100, 
                 facecolor = 'w', 
                 edgecolor = 'k')

# Here we state that our figure has 1 row, 2 columns.
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(1,2,1)
ax2 = fig.add_subplot(1,2,2)

ax1.set_title('First axes object');
ax2.set_title('Second axes object');

The above code to generate the figure and axes objects is largely illustrative. In practice and in tutorials, we most often see the figure and axes declared in one line.

Note: Generating a figure with more than one row or column results in the creation of an array of axes objects. We can access individual axes objects in this array by indexing.

In [52]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2)

axes methods¶

In the simplest cases, we'll be plotting some numeric values. An example of this is plotting the function $f(x) = x^2$, where $x$ is an array of 100 values between 0 and 1.

In [86]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

x = np.linspace(0,1,15)
y = x**2

ax.plot(x,y);

To plot individual data points instead of a smooth curve, we use the scatter() method.

In [58]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

x = np.linspace(0,1,100)
y = x**2

ax.scatter(x,y);

That's looking a little dense, so we can either reduce the number of points in x or change the marker to make the points easier to see.

In [59]:
# Reducing the number of points.

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

x = np.linspace(0,1,25)
y = x**2

ax.scatter(x,y);
In [62]:
# Changing the marker.

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

x = np.linspace(0,1,100)
y = x**2

ax.scatter(x,y, marker = '.');

In [95]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

x = np.linspace(0.1,1,25)

funcs = [np.sin(x), np.cos(x), x**2, np.log(x)]
marks = ['1',',','p','d']
legs = ['tri_up','pixel','pentagon','thin_diamond']

for f, m, leg in zip(funcs, marks, legs):
    ax.scatter(x, f, marker = m, label = leg)

ax.grid()
ax.legend();

This example illustrates 3 things:

  1. We can add a legend to the axes with the legend() method. The values in the legend are set by the label parameter in the plotting method.
  2. Creating a grid is done with the grid() method.
  3. We can overlay plots by simply plotting again after a single plot has been created.

Titles and axis labels can be added using the set_title(), set_xlabel(), and set_ylabel() methods.

In [96]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

x = np.linspace(0,1,100)
y = x**2

ax.plot(x,y);
ax.set_title('Plot of f(x)=x^2');
ax.set_xlabel('x');
ax.set_ylabel('y');

While this simple text is often enough for most cases, we can use LaTeX formatting for improved rendering of mathematical expressions.

In [97]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

Example: 2D scatterplot¶

When we talk about regression analysis, we'll refer to linear relationships between numerical variables. This assumption of linearity is often checked visually through a scatterplot.

In this example, we'll create a scatterplot of two numeric variables for two different datasets. We'll label our axes appropriately, set titles, and visually check if there might be linear relationships between variables.

In [98]:
# Dataset 1

data1_x = np.random.rand(150)
data1_y = data1_x + 0.1*np.random.randn(150)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.scatter(data1_x, data1_y)
ax.set_title(r'Scatterplot of $y$ vs $x$')
ax.set_xlabel(r'$x$')
ax.set_ylabel(r'$y$');

From the above scatterplot, it appears that there is a strong linear relationship between $x$ and $y$.

In [99]:
# Dataset 2

data2_x = np.random.rand(150)
data2_y = data2_x + 2*np.random.randn(150)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.scatter(data2_x, data2_y)
ax.set_title(r'Scatterplot of $y$ vs $x$')
ax.set_xlabel(r'$x$')
ax.set_ylabel(r'$y$');

From the above scatterplot, it appears that there is not a strong linear relationship between $x$ and $y$.

There are many other options for specifying plot styles. To set the locations of tick marks on either the horizontal or vertical axis, use the respective methods:

ax.set_xticks(<list of x-tick locations>)

or

ax.set_yticks(<list of y-tick locations>)

We may also turn the grid on or off using

ax.grid(<boolean>)

Types of plots in Matplotlib¶

We can display many more plots than just line plots and scatterplots. For example, we can represent 3D data in a 2D plot with the contour, contourf, or pcolormesh plots.

Note: we can use the set() method to set a wide range of plot attributes by keyworded argument (or dictionary).

In [108]:
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(-1,1,200),np.linspace(-1,1,200))

z = np.exp(-(xx**2 + yy**2))/np.sqrt(2*np.pi)
    
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize = (12,4))

ax[0].contour(xx, yy, z, levels = 25, cmap = 'hot')
ax[0].set(title = 'Contour plot', aspect = 'equal')

ax[1].contourf(xx, yy, z, levels = 25, cmap = 'hot')
ax[1].set(title = 'Filled contour plot', aspect = 'equal')

ax[2].pcolormesh(xx,yy,z, cmap = 'hot')
ax[2].set(title = 'Pseudo-colormesh plot', aspect = 'equal');

A less-used but visually striking plot is the hexplot.

In [109]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.hexbin(yy, z, gridsize=50, cmap='hot');
ax.set(title = 'Side view of gaussian function (hex plot)', 
       xlim = [-1,1], 
       xlabel = 'y', 
       ylabel = 'z');

For continuous numerical data, we can display the histogram using hist.

In [110]:
heights = np.random.normal(172, 10, 2500)
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.hist(heights, bins = 100);
ax.set(title = 'Histogram of male height',
       xlabel = 'Height (cm)', 
       ylabel = 'Frequency');

Bar charts¶

Plotting categorical data in bar charts is done with the bar and barh functions.

In [111]:
city = ['Calgary','Edmonton','Lethbridge','Medicine Hat','Red Deer']
trai = np.random.randint(1,10,5)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize = (15,4))

ax[0].bar(city, trai)
ax[0].set_title('Bar chart')

ax[1].barh(city, trai)
ax[1].set_title('Horizontal bar chart');

Pie charts¶

Pie charts are plotted with the pie() method of the ax object.

In [117]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.pie(trai, labels = city, colors = ['k','r','pink','m','purple']);

For smaller pieces of the pie, we can remove the piece from the pie with the explode argument. For this argument, we pass in a list with a float in the same index position as the piece we want to highlight. We'll also add a shadow and percentage labels.

In [120]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.pie(trai, 
       labels = city, 
       explode = [0, 0.5, 0, 0, 0], 
       shadow = True, 
       autopct = '%1.1f%%', 
       colors = ['green','purple','yellow','blue','cyan']);

Many different plots can be generated from pandas objects. The plot() method is essentially a wrapper for Matplotlib, meaning it serves as a go-between for using Matplotlib. Therefore, knowing Matplotlib should make plotting pandas objects easier to customize.

The main difference between this plotting method and plotting directly from the pandas object is customizability. We are now dealing directly with an ax object, so we can easily change its attributes after the fact.

                       title = 'World population (millions) by continent');

ax.set(xlim = [0, 500], xlabel = r'x 1,000,000', facecolor = 'b');

Saving plots¶

A variety of file formats are available for storing Matplotlib plots. Some common file extensions for pixel-based images are .jpg, .png, .tif/.tiff, and .gif. Scalable Vector Graphics (svg) files are also image files optimized for use on the web and are an excellent choice for saving our plots. These files are essentially XML files that allow the image to be smoothly scaled to any size.

Saving plots is done with the plt.savefig() function. The saved file format is specified with the format argument. Valid values for the format argument are svg, jpg, png, pdf, and ps.

In [127]:
fig, ax = plt.figure(), pop['Population'].plot(kind = 'barh',
                       title = 'World population (millions) by continent');

fig.savefig('worldpop.svg')
fig.savefig('worldpop.png')

Example: ANOVA with visualizations¶

Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) is a statistical technique for comparing mean differences of two or more treatments or populations. As with any hypothesis-testing procedure, we must know the null and alternative hypotheses before we begin the computations. We'll adopt the notation from (Gravetter & Wallnau, 2013).

In ANOVA, the null hypothesis is that there is no significant mean difference between populations. Put mathematically, if we are comparing $k$ populations or treatment groups: $$ H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2 = \cdots = \mu_k. $$

The alternative hypothesis is that there is a statistically significant difference between the population means. In other words: $$ H_A: \mu_1 \neq \mu_2 \neq \cdots \neq \mu_k. $$

Note: only one of the population means must be different in order to reject the null hypothesis. The notation for our alternative hypothesis is just for convenience.

In order to decide whether we fail to reject the null hypothesis or not, we compute the $F$-statistic, which is computed as $$ F = \frac{\text{variance between treatments}}{\text{variance within treatments}}. $$

There are several computations involved in performing ANOVA. We need not write code to compute each of these, since we can use packages.

Suppose we have completed an experiment in which we administered two different brands (Brand A and Brand B) of fertilizer to tomato plants. We want to test if there is a difference between the two brands in plant height after 2 months. If there is a difference, we can recommend one brand as being better than the other.

We will assume that we have 20 plants assigned to each brand of fertilizer, and we have an additional 20 plants given no fertilizer. All other variables, such as pre-fertilizer soil content, soil acidity, water, and light are kept constant. The data is kept in the tomato.csv dataset.

By looking at the boxplot, it appears that there is a difference in means between the three treatment groups. We'll now compute the ANOVA using the f_oneway() function from the SciPy package (SciPy is an extension of NumPy).

In [145]:
from scipy import stats

F, p = stats.f_oneway(tomato['Control'], tomato['Brand A'], tomato['Brand B'])
print('F-value: {:.4f}\np-value: {:.4f}'.format(F,p))

F-value: 48.6548
p-value: 0.0000

The above output is not very appealing, but it tells us that there is a statistically significant difference between the treatment groups (the $p$-value is far less than 0.05).

Another method of computing ANOVA is with the statsmodels package. A huge benefit of this package is the greatly improved readability of its output. The example below considers the ANOVA as a special case of a general linear model (GLM). What this basically means is that the treatment effect is considered a linear function of the treatment group.

To apply the 'statsmodels' method, we'll rearrange the data from above to make it easier to input to the ols() function. This is exactly the same data as above, just organized differently.

Example: Linear regression with visualizations - Synthetic data¶

The purpose of this example is to illustrate plotting a line of best fit over a scatterplot. We'll create a random variable y that depends on a second random variable x. In other words, we'll assume the linear relationship $$ y = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \varepsilon, $$ where $\varepsilon$ is random noise with mean 0 and variance 1.

To find the coefficients $\beta_0$ and $\beta_1$, we'll fit a linear regression using the statsmodels package.

In [153]:
x = np.random.rand(200)
y = x + 0.18*np.random.randn(200)

example_data = pd.DataFrame({'x': x, 'y': y})

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.scatter(x, y, color = 'b')
ax.set(title = r'Scatterplot of $y$ vs $x$', 
       xlabel = r'$x$', 
       ylabel = r'$y$', 
       xlim = [0, 1]);
In [154]:
# Fitting the model

model1 = ols('y ~ x', data = example_data).fit()
print(model1.summary())

                            OLS Regression Results                            
==============================================================================
Dep. Variable:                      y   R-squared:                       0.699
Model:                            OLS   Adj. R-squared:                  0.697
Method:                 Least Squares   F-statistic:                     459.1
Date:                Wed, 11 Mar 2020   Prob (F-statistic):           1.79e-53
Time:                        20:17:57   Log-Likelihood:                 58.479
No. Observations:                 200   AIC:                            -113.0
Df Residuals:                     198   BIC:                            -106.4
Df Model:                           1                                         
Covariance Type:            nonrobust                                         
==============================================================================
                 coef    std err          t      P>|t|      [0.025      0.975]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Intercept      0.0331      0.027      1.231      0.220      -0.020       0.086
x              0.9675      0.045     21.427      0.000       0.878       1.056
==============================================================================
Omnibus:                        4.383   Durbin-Watson:                   1.966
Prob(Omnibus):                  0.112   Jarque-Bera (JB):                5.620
Skew:                           0.065   Prob(JB):                       0.0602
Kurtosis:                       3.811   Cond. No.                         4.55
==============================================================================

Warnings:
[1] Standard Errors assume that the covariance matrix of the errors is correctly specified.

The output above shows that the Intercept ($\beta_0$) has approximate value 0.0331 and a $p$-value > 0.05, meaning that this coefficient is not statistically significant.

Similarly, the 'x' coefficient ($\beta_1$) has approximate value 0.9675 and $p$-value ~ 0.

There are two methods for producing the line of best fit:

  • We could generate a new sample of $x$-values and predict the corresponding $y$-values based on the model. To get the predictions, we would either use the model.predict(x_pred) method, or we could generate predictions ourselves by the formula $$

      \text{y}_p = 0.0331 + 0.9675x_p,

    $$ where $x_p$ are the $x$-values newly generated for prediction. To access the values of $\beta_0$ and $\beta_1$, we could call model1.params and grab the desired parameter by index.

  • Just use the statsmodels graphics.abline_plot() method. The arguments are the fitted model and the axes object for plotting.

Note: The ols object is picky about its inputs for its predict() method. It only accepts pandas DataFrame objects.

In [155]:
model1.params
Out[155]:
Intercept    0.033144
x            0.967457
dtype: float64
In [156]:
xp = pd.DataFrame(np.linspace(0,1,200))
yp = model1.predict(xp).sort_values()
In [158]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.scatter(x, y);
ax.plot(xp, yp, color = 'k');

We'll now plot the line of best fit using the graphics.abline_plot() method.

In [163]:
# Plotting the line of best fit over the scatterplot

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (12,5))

# Scatterplot of the data
ax.scatter(x, y, color = 'b')

# Plotting the line of best fit
sm.graphics.abline_plot(model_results = model1, ax = ax, color = 'r');
ax.set(title = 'Line of best fit for synthetic data', 
       xlabel = r'$x$', 
       ylabel = r'$y$');

Example: Linear regression with visualizations - Real data¶

Last day we explored the WHO data on the prevalence of depression across the world. Today we'll see if there might be a linear relationship between the prevalence of depression ($y$) and the number of psychiatrists ($x_1$) and psychologists ($x_2$). In particular, we want to know if we can predict $y$ given values of $x_1$ and $x_2$. For now, we'll assume the simple linear model $$ y = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \beta_2x_2 + \varepsilon. $$

Note: Remember that the number of doctors is given per 100,000 people. Note: We'll go into far more detail about regression next week. For now, we are more interested in the visuals.

Let's load in the data and make some plots. Because we want to check linearity, we'll plot $y$ vs $x_1$ and $y$ vs $x_2$.

Help on function abline_plot in module statsmodels.graphics.regressionplots:

abline_plot(intercept=None, slope=None, horiz=None, vert=None, model_results=None, ax=None, **kwargs)
    Plot a line given an intercept and slope.
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    intercept : float
        The intercept of the line.
    slope : float
        The slope of the line.
    horiz : float or array_like
        Data for horizontal lines on the y-axis.
    vert : array_like
        Data for verterical lines on the x-axis.
    model_results : statsmodels results instance
        Any object that has a two-value `params` attribute. Assumed that it
        is (intercept, slope).
    ax : axes, optional
        Matplotlib axes instance.
    **kwargs
        Options passed to matplotlib.pyplot.plt.
    
    Returns
    -------
    Figure
        The figure given by `ax.figure` or a new instance.
    
    Examples
    --------
    >>> import numpy as np
    >>> import statsmodels.api as sm
    
    >>> np.random.seed(12345)
    >>> X = sm.add_constant(np.random.normal(0, 20, size=30))
    >>> y = np.dot(X, [25, 3.5]) + np.random.normal(0, 30, size=30)
    >>> mod = sm.OLS(y,X).fit()
    >>> fig = sm.graphics.abline_plot(model_results=mod)
    >>> ax = fig.axes[0]
    >>> ax.scatter(X[:,1], y)
    >>> ax.margins(.1)
    >>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    >>> plt.show()
    
    .. plot:: plots/graphics_regression_abline.py

Summary¶

  • Matplotlib is the fundamental plotting library for Python. Almost all other plotting packages are based on Matplotlib.
  • The fundamental plotting objects are the figure and the axes.
  • Many types of common 2D plots are available through Matplotlib.
  • A collection of plotting examples is available at the Matplotlib Gallery.
  • ANOVA can be computed using the statsmodels package.
  • Linear regression can be computed using the statsmodels package, which has a module for visualizations.
